But Schnitzler’s liking for the pathological
type, the emotional aberration, the enigmatic
passion, though it perhaps made his stories
seem not quite real to English readers at
least, could not disguise a masterly and
delicate execution. No one ever treated the
and intrigue more lightly or more urbanely. He
had a nice sensibility and always avoided either
melodrama or mere prettiness. He knew to the
bottom the types he portrayed—the courtesan,
the profligate, the neurotic; they might
be in a grotesque or artificial setting, but they
were never anything but true to themselves
to the end. Schnitzler's powers of both
analysis and construction brought the short
novel, his most characteristic medium, te
something like perfection of form. His plots
were always neat and finished, if not original
and his writing always gripped. It was
pity only that in the last resort he was with-
